ategies of a Stammering Teen in David Mitchell's Black Swan Green -- tContributors -- tEditors -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aWhat makes a reading experience »powerful«? This volume brings together literary scholars, linguists, and empirical researchers to elucidate the effects and reader responses to investigate just that. The thirteen contributions theorize this widely-used, but to date insufficiently studied notion, and provide insights into the therefore still mysterious-seeming power of literary fiction. The collection investigates a variety of stylistic as well as readerly and psychological features responsible for short- and long-term effects - topics of great interest to those interested or specialized in literary studies and narratology, (cognitive) stylistics, empirical literary studies and reader response theory.  afunded by Max-Planck-Institut für empirische Ästhetik  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aLiteraturexAppreciationxPsychological aspects. 0aLiteraturexHistory and criticism. 4aCulture. 4aLanguage. 4aLinguistics. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPsychology. 4aTheory of Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aCulture.  aLanguage.  aLinguistics.  aLiterary Studies.  aPsychology.  aTheory of Literature.1 aBoisseau, Maryvonne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChollier, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKavanagh, Ciarán, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLabourg, Alice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vo